{\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24\par}\pard\plain\itap0\s0\fi0\sb200\sa0\aspalpha\aspnum\adjustright\ltrpar\li0\lin0\ri0\rin0\qj\faauto\sl260\slmult0\rtlch\afs24\ltrch\fs24{\*\bkmkstart Bookmark_para_10}{\*\bkmkend Bookmark_para_10}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24
\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 It is undisputed that neither the engineer nor fireman saw or could see the perilous position of the stranger, because the engine was around the curve near the Wells Fargo Express Building. This would end the case in favor of defendant, had it been a train going from station to station, and operated as such trains ordinarily are. For on such a train the engineer directs and controls its movement, and if one who is guilty of negligence in being on or too near the track is not discovered by him or his fireman to be in peril in time, by the use of the means at hand, to prevent injuring him, there is no actionable negligence. But in switching cars in a populous city the engineer is governed in the control and operation of his engine by signals communicated to him by the}
{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 \~[**12]\~}{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2
\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3  switchmen, who are, metaphorically speaking, the eyes of the engineer, used in discovering persons or objects on or near the tracks over which the switching is being done. And whenever a person is seen on or near the track in a position of peril by a switchman who is in a position to signal the engineer to stop his engine in time to prevent injuring him, it is as though the engineer himself had discovered the peril of the party. In this case, the stranger was discovered on or near the track over which the cars were being switched by two of the switchmen, the deceased and Frank Ash. The former was not in a position to communicate a signal of such discovery to the engineer. The latter was, and by signaling the engineer the cars could have been stopped in time to have prevented his injury, for the evidence shows that they were moving very slowly, at the rate only of about two miles an hour. But Ash gave no signal, but let the cars run on, catch, and kill his fellow switchman, who had saved the stranger's life at the sacrifice of his own.}
